80","1243–1327":"1243–1327","1280–1364":"1280–1364","1228–1261":"1228–1261","1232–Female":"1232–Deceased","1228":"1228","1327":"1327","Between 1258 and 1261":"from 1258 to 1261","1259":"1259","1279":"1279","1254":"1254","1232":"1232","1364":"1364","1243":"1243","1261":"1261","1280":"1280","Angleterre":"England","Somerset County, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","Trumpington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Trumpington, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":5,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud de Trumpington was born in 1254, in Trumpington, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Everard de Trumpington, was 26 and her mother, Maud of Cambridgeshire, was 23. She married Walter Reynell V in 1279, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1280, in Cambridgeshire, England, at the age of 26, and was buried in England."},"et":{"1254–1280":"1254–1280","1243–1327":"1243–1327","1280–1364":"1280–1364","1228–1261":"1228–1261","1232–Female":"1232–Surnud","1228":"1228","1327":"1327","Between 1258 and 1261":"1258 kuni 1261","1259":"1259","1279":"1279","1254":"1254","1232":"1232","1364":"1364","1243":"1243","1261":"1261","1280":"1280","Angleterre":"England","Somerset County, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","Trumpington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Trumpington, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1254–1280":"1254–1280","1243–1327":"1243–1327","1280–1364":"1280–1364","1228–1261":"1228–1261","1232–Female":"1232–Kuollut","1228":"1228","1327":"1327","Between 1258 and 1261":"vuodesta 1258 vuoteen 1261","1259":"1259","1279":"1279","1254":"1254","1232":"1232","